-- ===== Set Current_Value to match the real UI pattern =====
-- What we saw in the production UI:
--   * Single items (IsIndividual = 1) -> Current_Value equals Cost (one unit).
--   * Multiple items (IsIndividual = 0) -> Current_Value is HIGHER than Cost,
--     because in the real system it is a TOTAL value across all the units,
--     not a per-unit figure.
-- These are plausible TEST values only. The real app has its own valuation
-- logic we don't need to copy -- the chatbot just reports whatever is stored
-- here, so the numbers only need to LOOK like production, not be accounting-
-- correct. The multiplier is intentionally a small spread (about 1.15x to
-- 1.54x, varied by Asset_ID) so the data doesn't look obviously generated.
-- The scrapped row (AST-009, IsDelete = 1) is left untouched.
UPDATE dbo.Asset
SET Current_Value = CASE
        WHEN IsIndividual = 1 THEN Cost
        ELSE ROUND(Cost * (1.15 + (Asset_ID % 40) / 100.0), 2)
    END
WHERE IsDelete = 0;
GO

